<node TEXT="Note that due to the rays starting on the glass interface being metric, in theory, relative pose as described here on underwater cameras can yield the absolute distance to&#xd;&#xa;the second camera as opposed to perspective relative pose, where the baseline to the second camera is usually scaled to one.&#xd;&#xa;Relative pose in the refractive case is not invariant to scale changes in the camera translation.&#x6298;&#x5c04;&#x60c5;&#x51b5;&#x4e0b;&#xff0c;&#x76f8;&#x673a;&#x5e73;&#x79fb;&#x8fc7;&#x7a0b;&#x4e2d;&#x76f8;&#x673a;&#x4f4d;&#x7f6e;&#x4e0d;&#x662f;&#x5c3a;&#x5ea6;&#x4e0d;&#x53d8;&#x7684;&#xff0c;&#x56e0;&#x4e3a;&#x6298;&#x5c04;&#x754c;&#x9762;&#x7684;&#x539a;&#x5ea6;&#x548c;&#x8ddd;&#x79bb;&#x4e0d;&#x53d8;" ID="ID_1071501851" CREATED="1501313514644" MODIFIED="1501313514644" LINK="project://15D6452E29D9SKCYL8S32EEF1MB7Z0BV75KJ/literature_repository/papers/Calibration%203D_Reconstruction/2013%20Refractive%20structure-from-motion%20on%20Underwater%20Images.pdf">
